No, we wouldn't.  We also would probably not put up with computer
technology that just stayed static.  The users seem to want these
machines to be able to do more and more.  100% back-compatibility
is not always possible if we want to move forward.

Your machine still works fine, apparently, and you can use it to
do what it does for as long as you want.  The trade-off is that
you'll be stuck with what you have and won't necessarily be able
to use the "latest and greatest".  If that's ok, then it's ok to
get off the train <g>.

